<subSubSection id="3B8B24AAFFC6FFC5FEAA2760D9CAF8B2" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="732E7721FFC6FFC5FEAA2760D9CAF8B2" blockId="17.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC6FFC5FEAA2760DBB2F911" bold="true" box="[312,444,1643,1669]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Discussion</emphasis>
. Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="B4910CA2FFC6FFC5FDC22767D923F912" authority="Painter" authorityName="Painter" box="[592,813,1644,1670]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC6FFC5FDC22767D8DEF911" box="[592,720,1644,1669]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. argutus</emphasis>
Painter
</taxonomicName>
in pilosity and color of tomentum. In the male genitalia the presence of two projections on the lower margin of the gonocoxa in 
<taxonomicName id="B4910CA2FFC6FFC5FA9C279FDB87F941" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albipilosus">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC6FFC5FA9C279FDB87F941" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. albipilosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
versus only one in 
<taxonomicName id="B4910CA2FFC6FFC5FDE627B7D8FFF941" box="[628,753,1724,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC6FFC5FDE627B7D8FFF941" box="[628,753,1724,1749]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. argutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
will distinguish the males. The females may be recognized by the characteristic vaginal furca: the swollen apices of the lower struts are pointed inward in 
<taxonomicName id="B4910CA2FFC6FFC5FE4C2607D88DF8B1" box="[478,643,1804,1829]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albipilosus">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC6FFC5FE4C2607D88DF8B1" box="[478,643,1804,1829]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. albipilosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and outward in 
<taxonomicName id="B4910CA2FFC6FFC5FCD32607D9B3F8B1" box="[833,957,1804,1829]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Geron" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="argutus">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC6FFC5FCD32607D9B3F8B1" box="[833,957,1804,1829]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">G. argutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3B8B24AAFFC6FFC5FEAA2638DE35F8DA" box="[312,1083,1843,1870]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="732E7721FFC6FFC5FEAA2638DE35F8DA" blockId="17.[264,1324,284,1870]" box="[312,1083,1843,1870]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC6FFC5FEAA2638DB9AF8D9" bold="true" box="[312,404,1843,1869]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Biology</emphasis>
. Immature stages and adult flower preferences unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3B8B24AAFFC5FFC6FEAA2010DE56FE12" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="732E7721FFC5FFC6FEAA2010DE56FE12" blockId="18.[264,1322,283,390]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC5FFC6FEAA2010DBDFFEA1" bold="true" box="[312,465,283,309]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC5FFC6FE4D2010D888FEA1" bold="true" box="[479,646,283,309]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<collectingCountry id="0B8637B1FFC5FFC6FE4D2010D888FEA1" box="[479,646,283,309]" name="United States of America" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">United States</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
(California, Colorado, Nevada, New 
<collectingCountry id="0B8637B1FFC5FFC6FBAD2017DE92FEA2" box="[1087,1180,284,310]" name="Mexico" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, Utah). 
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC5FFC6FEAA2048DBB3FEC9" bold="true" box="[312,445,323,349]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet derives from the Latin “ 
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC5FFC6FC4F204FDE04FEC9" box="[989,1034,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">albi</emphasis>
­“ = white, + “ 
<emphasis id="41E5AB33FFC5FFC6FB28204FDF03FEC9" box="[1210,1293,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">pilosus</emphasis>
”= hair; referring to the predominantly pale colored vestiture of this species
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
